 1195.","1235":"1235","1244":"1244","Abt 1160":"oko 1160.","1329":"1329","1207":"1207","Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"cs":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1207":"okolo 1160–okolo 1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1192–1244":"1192–1244","1227–Male":"1227–Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1190":"1190","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","Abt 1207":"okolo 1207","1192":"1192","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"okolo 1195","1235":"1235","1244":"1244","Abt 1160":"okolo 1160","1329":"1329","1207":"1207","Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"da":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1207":"omkring 1160–omkring 1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1192–1244":"1192–1244","1227–Male":"1227–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1190":"1190","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","Abt 1207":"omkring 1207","1192":"1192","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"omkring 1195","1235":"1235","1244":"1244","Abt 1160":"omkring 1160","1329":"1329","1207":"1207","Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1207":"circa 1160–circa 1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1192–1244":"1192–1244","1227–Male":"1227–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1190":"1190","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","Abt 1207":"circa 1207","1192":"1192","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"circa 1195","1235":"1235","1244":"1244","Abt 1160":"circa 1160","1329":"1329","1207":"1207","Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Schotland"},"en":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1207":"about 1160–about 1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1192–1244":"1192–1244","1227–Male":"1227–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1190":"1190","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","Abt 1207":"about 1207","1192":"1192","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"about 1195","1235":"1235","1244":"1244","Abt 1160":"about 1160","1329":"1329","1207":"1207","Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester Castle, Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Giffard was born about 1160 as the son of Hugh Giffard. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs William Giffard. He died about 1207, at the age of 49."},"et":{"Abt 1160–Abt 1207":"umbes 1160–umbes 1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1192–1244":"1192–1244","1227–Male":"1227–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1190–1235":"1190–1235","1250–1329":"1250–1329","1130–1195":"1130–1195","1190":"1190","1130":"1130","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","Abt 1207":"umbes 1207","1192":"1192","1227":"1227","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","1235":"1235","1244":"1244","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","1329":"1329","1207":"1207","Yes